<subSubSection id="7C85650B6C6CFF87FF71FE23FCE7F47D" pageId="10" pageNumber="363" type="nomenclature">
<paragraph id="342036806C6CFF87FF71FE23FDBDF78D" blockId="10.[166,595,447,474]" box="[166,595,447,474]" pageId="10" pageNumber="363">
<heading id="6F6881EC6C6CFF87FF71FE23FDBDF78D" box="[166,595,447,474]" fontSize="36" level="2" pageId="10" pageNumber="363" reason="3">
<taxonomicName id="F39F4D036C6CFF87FF71FE23FDBDF78D" authority="de Graslin, 1855" authorityName="de Graslin" authorityYear="1855" box="[166,595,447,474]" class="Insecta" family="Noctuidae" genus="Heliothis" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="10" pageNumber="363" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="maritima">
<emphasis id="06EBEA926C6CFF87FF71FE23FE61F78E" bold="true" box="[166,399,447,474]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="363">Heliothis maritima</emphasis>
de Graslin, 1855
</taxonomicName>
</heading>
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="342036806C6CFF87FF0CFE73FCE7F47D" blockId="10.[166,1225,495,810]" pageId="10" pageNumber="363">
D e s c r i p t i o n. Egg subspherical (
<figureCitation id="ACA42A056C6CFF87FDAAFE73FD25F45D" box="[637,715,495,522]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="6.[163,196,1732,1754]" captionTargetBox="[166,1224,188,1666]" captionTargetId="figure-8@6.[166,1224,188,1666]" captionTargetPageId="6" captionText="Fig. 25–30. Eggs of Cuculliinae: 25–27 — Cucullia xeranthemi; 28 — Cucullia umbratica; eggs of Heliothinae: 29, 30 — Heliothis maritima. Scale bars: 25, 29 — 100 µm; 26–28, 30 — 10 µm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6453296" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6453296/files/figure.png" pageId="10" pageNumber="363">fig. 29</figureCitation>
), height 
<quantity id="F3679B656C6CFF87FCE5FE73FC61F45D" box="[818,911,495,522]" metricMagnitude="-4" metricUnit="m" metricValue="4.0" pageId="10" pageNumber="363" unit="mm" value="0.4">0.4 mm</quantity>
, diameter 
<quantity id="F3679B656C6CFF87FBDBFE73FB89F45D" box="[1036,1127,495,522]" metricMagnitude="-4" metricUnit="m" metricValue="6.0" pageId="10" pageNumber="363" unit="mm" value="0.6">0.6 mm</quantity>
(n = 2). Fresh egg citron colour. Chorion white, translucent.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="7C85650B6C6CFF87FF0CFDB3FD9FF50D" pageId="10" pageNumber="363" type="description">
<paragraph id="342036806C6CFF87FF0CFDB3FB65F4BD" blockId="10.[166,1225,495,810]" pageId="10" pageNumber="363">
Chorion ridged, marked on two thirds surfaces. Micropylar area represented by rosette and 1 row of weakly expressed cells (
<figureCitation id="ACA42A056C6CFF87FD74FDD3FD1CF43D" box="[675,754,591,618]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="6.[163,196,1732,1754]" captionTargetBox="[166,1224,188,1666]" captionTargetId="figure-8@6.[166,1224,188,1666]" captionTargetPageId="6" captionText="Fig. 25–30. Eggs of Cuculliinae: 25–27 — Cucullia xeranthemi; 28 — Cucullia umbratica; eggs of Heliothinae: 29, 30 — Heliothis maritima. Scale bars: 25, 29 — 100 µm; 26–28, 30 — 10 µm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6453296" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6453296/files/figure.png" pageId="10" pageNumber="363">fig. 30</figureCitation>
). Rosette elevated with 15–16 long and narrow cells and 5 micropylar opening 
<emphasis id="06EBEA926C6CFF87FDAEFDF3FD6AF4DE" bold="true" box="[633,644,623,649]" pageId="10" pageNumber="363">s</emphasis>
. Walls of cells elevated (
<figureCitation id="ACA42A056C6CFF87FC7AFDF3FC15F4DD" box="[941,1019,623,650]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="7.[170,203,1728,1750]" captionTargetBox="[174,1232,197,1686]" captionTargetId="figure-5@7.[174,1232,196,1686]" captionTargetPageId="7" captionText="Fig. 31–36. Eggs of Heliothinae: 31–32 — Heliothis maritima; 33–35 — Helicoverpa armigera; eggs of Condicinae: 36 — Eucarta amethystina. Scale bars: 33, 36 — 100 µm. 31, 32, 34–35 — 10 µm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6453300" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6453300/files/figure.png" pageId="10" pageNumber="363">fig. 31</figureCitation>
). There are 14 of 36 clearly expressed longitudinal ridges radiate from cells of first row. Longest ridges with high combs especially in apical part (
<figureCitation id="ACA42A056C6CFF87FD86FD33FD73F49D" box="[593,669,687,714]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="7.[170,203,1728,1750]" captionTargetBox="[174,1232,197,1686]" captionTargetId="figure-5@7.[174,1232,196,1686]" captionTargetPageId="7" captionText="Fig. 31–36. Eggs of Heliothinae: 31–32 — Heliothis maritima; 33–35 — Helicoverpa armigera; eggs of Condicinae: 36 — Eucarta amethystina. Scale bars: 33, 36 — 100 µm. 31, 32, 34–35 — 10 µm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6453300" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6453300/files/figure.png" pageId="10" pageNumber="363">fig. 32</figureCitation>
). Transverse walls less distinct and narrow than ridges. Aeropyles weakly expressed. The entire surface of small, densely placed fibers.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="342036806C6CFF87FF0CFD73FEBBF57D" blockId="10.[166,1225,495,810]" pageId="10" pageNumber="363">
Shape of gnawed holes in eggs. Caterpillar nibbles out large oval opening at lateral part of egg (
<figureCitation id="ACA42A056C6CFF87FF2CFC93FEA6F57D" box="[251,328,783,810]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="6.[163,196,1732,1754]" captionTargetBox="[166,1224,188,1666]" captionTargetId="figure-8@6.[166,1224,188,1666]" captionTargetPageId="6" captionText="Fig. 25–30. Eggs of Cuculliinae: 25–27 — Cucullia xeranthemi; 28 — Cucullia umbratica; eggs of Heliothinae: 29, 30 — Heliothis maritima. Scale bars: 25, 29 — 100 µm; 26–28, 30 — 10 µm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6453296" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6453296/files/figure.png" pageId="10" pageNumber="363">fig. 29</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="342036806C6CFF87FF0CFCA3FD9FF50D" blockId="10.[219,625,831,858]" box="[219,625,831,858]" pageId="10" pageNumber="363">O v i p o s i t i o n. Eggs solitary laid.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
</treatment>
